DIAPEN SIACRAE (handwritten)

FAMILY: DIAPENSIACEAE
PLANTS OF VIRGINIA
THE MORTON ARBORETUM, LISLE, IL 60532
Roanoke Co.
Col.No.: MWPCC00-002

*Galax urceolata* (Poir.) Brummitt

Jefferson Natl. Forest, Numerous plants scattered across the slope above
Trail leading to Dragon's Tooth parking lot, under an open canopy of:
*Nyssa sylvatica*, *Acer rubrum*, *Quercus prinus*, *Pinus strobus*, *Oxydendrum arboreum*, rich understory includes *Hamamelis virginiana*, *Asarum*, *Goodyera* sp., *Buckleya distichophylla*, *Acer pensylvanicum*, *Kalmia latifolia*, *Pieris floribunda*, *Viburnum acerifolium*. 30-45 S facing slope, clay soil with shale fragments, thin organic layer. Foliage to 3", flowering stems 1 ft. Small yellowish-brown fruit.
Lat.: 37 22.697'N, Long.: 80 9.360'W
Col. By: A.Aiello, J. Ault, K. Kim, C. Tubesing Altitude: 1,740 ft.
Sept. 12, 2000

IMAGED
Morris Arboretum, Univ. of Penn.
